articles.author: JOSH BOAK, STEPHEN GROVES and LISA MASCARO
articles.description: WASHINGTON (AP) — The White House on Friday directed federal agencies to get ready for a shutdown after House Republicans left town for the weekend with no viable plan to keep the government funded and avert politically and economically costly disruption of federal services.
articles.title: White House preparing for government shutdown as House Republicans lack a viable endgame for funding

articles.author: STEPHEN GROVES
articles.description: WASHINGTON (AP) — The federal government is heading toward a shutdown that will disrupt many services, squeeze workers and roil politics as Republicans in the House, fueled by hard-right demands for deep cuts, force a confrontation over federal spending.
articles.title: The federal government is headed into a shutdown. What does it mean, who's hit and what's next?

articles.author: The Associated Press
articles.description: Why Yevgeny Prigozhin's private jet plummeted into a field northwest of Moscow is still a mystery. The Russian military leaders he tried to oust with his armed rebellion remain in power. His mercenary army is under new management.
articles.title: A month after Prigozhin’s suspicious death, the Kremlin is silent on his plane crash and legacy

articles.author: JAKE OFFENHARTZ
articles.description: NEW YORK (AP) — In late 2020, Sen. Bob Menendez met with Philip Sellinger, a private practice lawyer and former fundraiser for the senator, to assess his potential fit as the next U.S. Attorney for the state of New Jersey — and to discuss one case in particular.
articles.title: Bribery case against Sen. Menendez shines light on powerful NJ developer accused of corruption

articles.author: JAMEY KEATEN, MATTHEW LEE and VANESSA GERA
articles.description: WARSAW, Poland (AP) — Once rock-solid, the support that Ukraine has gotten from its biggest backers for its fight against Russia is showing cracks. Political posturing in places like Poland and Slovakia, where a trade dispute with Ukraine has stirred tensions, and Republican reticence in the United States about Washington’s big spending to prop up Ukraine’s military have raised new uncertainties about the West’s commitment to its efforts to expel Russian invaders more than 18 months into the war.
articles.title: Cracks in Western wall of support for Ukraine emerge as Eastern Europe and US head toward elections

articles.author: REGINA GARCIA CANO and ELLIOT SPAGAT
articles.description: MEXICO CITY (AP) — From a White House podium in May, U.S. Homeland Security Secretary Alejandro Mayorkas outlined new legal pathways to the United States for Venezuelans and others, along with a “very clear” message for those come illegally.
articles.title: With temporary status for Venezuelans, the Biden administration turns to a familiar tool

articles.author: NICOLE WINFIELD and SYLVIE CORBET
articles.description: MARSEILLE, France (AP) — Pope Francis challenged French President Emmanuel Macron and other European leaders to open their ports to people fleeing hardship and poverty, insisting Saturday that the continent does not face a migration “emergency” but rather a long-term reality that governments must deal with humanely.
articles.title: Pope Francis insists Europe doesn't have a migrant emergency and challenges countries to open ports

articles.author: SARAH BRUMFIELD and BRIAN WITTE
articles.description: ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) — Tropical Storm Ophelia made landfall on the North Carolina coast early Saturday, lashing coastal areas with damaging winds and dangerous surges of water, the U.S. National Hurricane Center said.
articles.title: Tropical Storm Ophelia makes landfall in North Carolina as coastal areas lashed with heavy rain

articles.author: EDITH M. LEDERER
articles.description: UNITED NATIONS (AP) — At the annual meeting of world leaders last year, the U.N. chief sounded a global alarm about the survival of humanity and the planet. This year, the alarm rang louder and more ominously, and the message was even more pressing: Wake up and take action — right now.
articles.title: As the world's problems grow more challenging, the head of the United Nations gets bleaker

articles.author: MEG KINNARD
articles.description: COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) — As a state representative running a longshot campaign for South Carolina governor, Nikki Haley would often explain her opposition to abortion with a story about her family.“I’m strongly pro-life, very pro-life, and not because my party tells me to be, but my husband was adopted, and so every day I know the blessings of having him there,” she said in 2010.
articles.title: Nikki Haley's approach to abortion is rooted in her earliest days in South Carolina politics
